{"questionId": "df7af07f-1de4-419a-83e5-dadc9e1caefe_17", "correctAnswer": "C", "section": "Reading and Writing", "steps": [{"title": "Identify where the descriptive clause must go", "content": "The key signal is the clause “which are skeletal muscles.” When a clause describes a noun and is not essential to the main meaning of the sentence, it must appear right after that noun and be enclosed by commas on both sides."}, {“title”: “Apply the rule to the choices”, “content”: “Choice C places the clause immediately after the subject with commas on both sides, then continues with the main predicates \”are cylindrical in shape and help move the fibula and humerus, respectively.\” &#10003;<br/><br/><ul><li><strong>Choice A</strong>: Places \”which are skeletal muscles\” after \”cylindrical in shape\” rather than after the noun it modifies, separating the clause from the noun it describes. A stray comma after \”help\” further breaks the sentence. &#10007;</li><li><strong>Choice B</strong>: Inserts the clause after \”help,\” placing it far from the noun it modifies and breaking up the verb phrase \”help move the fibula and humerus.\” &#10007;</li><li><strong>Choice D</strong>: Inserts the clause inside the phrase \”cylindrical in shape,\” splitting that phrase apart rather than following the noun with a properly paired comma clause. &#10007;</li></ul>That matches choice C &mdash; <strong>C</strong> is correct.”}]}